import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from keras.engine import Model
from keras.layers import Input, Dense, Dropout
from keras.optimizers import RMSprop, Adamax

inputs = Input(shape=(216,))

nw = Dense(unit_number, activation='relu')(inputs)
#nw = Dropout(.2)(nw)
nw = Dense(unit_number, activation='relu')(nw)   
nw = Dense(unit_number, activation='relu')(nw)   
predictions = Dense(5, activation='softmax')(nw)

model = Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=predictions)

model.compile(optimizer='Adamax',
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

data = x_train
labels = y_train
model.fit(data, labels)

classes = model.predict(x_test, batch_size=128)

val_data = x_test
val_labels = y_test
history = model.fit(data, labels, batch_size=256, epochs=160, verbose=0, validation_data=(val_data, val_labels))

plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# 1 Introduction

Some molecules are rigid, but some other molecules are flexible. Flexible molecules change their shapes in the environment, and sometimes they move in the solid state. This motion is similar to that of a pendulum moving in a pendulum clock. It is almost impossible to see the molecular motion because it is very fast. So, we can see only the average shape.
![CoDMSOrt.gif](attachment:CoDMSOrt.gif)
The question is how to know the molecular motion from something like a still image with averaged shapes. As the first step, I aimed to reveal the most stable shape of a flexible molecule, because the most stable shape is expected to be observed most frequently. The number of possible shapes was mathematically estimated to be 130. The energy of each shape was calculated and the 130 shapes were ranked from the most stable to the least stable. However, this took two months.
In order to save time, I decided to introduce machine learning (ML) technique. That is, if the top 20% is successfullly predicted by ML beforehand, the calculation time will be one fifth.
